KNEE INJURIES - PART 1

PATELLA DISLOCATION

Swipe left to gain an understanding of how the patella can dislocate out of the trochlear groove in certain situations.

Reduction of the patella ie. putting the kneecap back into place is quite simple and only requires extending the patients affected leg. This shortens the length of the quadriceps and forces the patella to slip back into the trochlear groove.

Treatment and management following patellar dislocation typically involves a ROM restriction brace in order to promote healing of the medial structures in a shortened position.

Historically, the VMO has been the focal point of rehab following patellar dislocation. Evidence to suggest that one would be able to selectively recruit the VMO is scarce.

Instead, rehab should focus on hip and knee joint stability specifically when the left leg is planted in preparation for right leg kicking. Perhaps an in depth analysis of this players kicking biomechanics should also take place as his left leg is clearly excessively flexed and externally rotated.

Credit: @gdphysio
